  <static seed="1301" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions5.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{9+\frac{1}{x}}}{{x+3}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{9x+1}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+3\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{9+\frac{1}{x}}}{{x+3}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{9+\frac{1}{x}}</m> and <m>{x+3}</m>, which is <m>{x}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{9+\frac{1}{x}}}{{x+3}} \amp = \frac{({9+\frac{1}{x}})\cdot{x}}{({x+3})\cdot{x}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{9x+1}}{{x\mathopen{}\left(x+3\right)}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Although <m>{x}</m> was canceled, <m>x \ne 0</m> is implied in the solution. There is no need to treat <m>x \ne 0</m> as a lost condition.</p>
</solution>
